<section class="page-hero"><div class="container"><small>HELP YOUR PLANTS THRIVE</small><h1>Plant care guide</h1><p>Simple routines for healthier indoor plants in San Francisco.</p></div></section><section class="section"><div class="container info-grid"><article><i class="fa-regular fa-sun"></i><h2>Light</h2><p>Most tropical houseplants prefer bright, indirect light. Rotate pots every two weeks for even growth.</p></article><article><i class="fa-solid fa-droplet"></i><h2>Water</h2><p>Check the top two inches of soil before watering. Empty saucers so roots never remain in standing water.</p></article><article><i class="fa-solid fa-wind"></i><h2>Humidity</h2><p>Keep tropical plants away from heaters and cold drafts. Grouping plants can improve local humidity.</p></article><article><i class="fa-solid fa-seedling"></i><h2>Soil and feeding</h2><p>Use a well-draining mix and fertilize lightly during spring and summer.</p></article><article><i class="fa-solid fa-bug"></i><h2>Pest checks</h2><p>Inspect leaf undersides weekly. Isolate affected plants and begin treatment early.</p></article><article><i class="fa-solid fa-scissors"></i><h2>Pruning</h2><p>Remove yellow leaves with clean scissors and trim leggy growth above a node.</p></article></div></section>